Visualization Tutorial

Leonardo Alchieri, Universit della Svizzera Italiana

10 Nov 2025, Istituto Nazionale dei Tumori, Milano

Example Description

I simulated data for a clinical trial. We have 100 patients randomized to three arms: High-dose treatment, Low-dose treatment and Placebo (control). We measure two biomarkers at 5 time points: 0, 1, 2, 4, 5. The actual value of the timepoints is not important for the tutorial. We separate the patients into responders and non-responders, based on their response to the treatment.

Disclaimer: The data is completely simulated and does not represent any real clinical trial.

You can find the data in ./data/clinical-example-1.xlsx

What we will do

  • Learn how to load data from Excel
  • Learn how to manipulate data with pandas library
  • Learn how to create displots with the seaborn library
  • Learn how to create lineplots with the seaborn library
  • Learn how to create boxplots with the seaborn library

Necessary Packages

You need to install the following packages

  • pandas
  • seaborn
  • matplotlib
  • openpyxl

Do you remember how to install packages?

Plotting Distributions

Seaborn is a high-level data visualization library. Seaborn relies on the pandas DataFrame structure.

Plot distribution of "Basophils" count for Non-Responders at TimePoint 2, for the "Low Dose" treatment arm

In[68]:
data_subset = data[
    (data["ARM"] == "Low Dose")
    & (data["Risposta"] == "Non-Responder")
    & (data["TimePoint"] == "T2")
]
display(data_subset.head())

In[69]:
sns.displot(data=data_subset, x="Basophils", kde=True)
plt.show()

You can use displot to also have 2D distributions

In[70]:
sns.displot(data=data_subset, x="Basophils", y="Neutrophils")
plt.show()
In[71]:
sns.displot(data=data_subset, x="Basophils", y="Neutrophils", kind='kde', rug=True)
plt.show()

Making sub-plots automatically

Seaborn allows to create subplots automatically, using the col and row arguments in displot.

Let's plot now the distribution of Basophils count at TimePoint 2, for Responders and Non-Responders, for all types of treatment arms.

In[76]:
data_subset = data[
    (data["TimePoint"] == "T2")
]
display(data_subset.head())
ID ARM TimePoint Risposta Basophils Neutrophils
1 1 High Dose T2 Responder 30001.500000 12000.600000
6 2 Low Dose T2 Responder 10005.000000 10005.000000
11 3 High Dose T2 Responder 12000.600000 30001.500000
16 4 High Dose T2 Responder 27237.592806 30001.500000
21 5 High Dose T2 Responder 30001.500000 29447.297843
In[77]:
sns.displot(
    data=data_subset,
    x="Basophils", 
    kind='kde', 
    hue="Risposta",
    col='ARM'
    )

plt.suptitle("Distribution of Basophils at TimePoint 2 by Response Status and Treatment Arm", y=1.02)
plt.savefig("data/displot_facet_arm.pdf", bbox_inches='tight')
plt.show()

Boxplot!

Now you should have a good idea of how to use seaborn. I'll you an example, and then you can try by yourself!

In[101]:
data_subset = data[
    (data["ARM"] == "High Dose")
]
display(data_subset.head())
ID ARM TimePoint Risposta Basophils Neutrophils
0 1 High Dose T1 Responder 12018.795950 11347.932198
1 1 High Dose T2 Responder 30001.500000 12000.600000
2 1 High Dose T3 Responder 18000.900000 45002.250000
3 1 High Dose T4 Responder 24001.200000 24001.200000
4 1 High Dose T5 Responder 44291.937567 74879.138932
In[]:
sns.catplot(
    data=data_subset, y='Basophils', x='TimePoint', hue="Risposta", 
    kind='box'
    )

plt.title("Boxplot of Basophils by TimePoint and Response Status (high-dose arm)")
plt.show()
In[81]:
sns.catplot(
    data=data_subset,
    x='Basophils',
    y='TimePoint',
    hue="Risposta",
    kind='violin',
    split=True,
    )

plt.grid(True)
plt.title("Boxplot of Basophils by TimePoint and Response Status (high-dose arm)")
plt.show()

Your turn!

Create a violin plot of Basophils count across TimePoints, for Responders and Non-Responders, in the "High Dose" treatment arm. Use rows and columns as before!

Lineplot

When you have temporal data (line the timepoints in our example), you can use lineplots to visualize trends over time.

In[]:
data_subset = data[(data['ARM'] == 'High Dose') 
                   & (data['Risposta'] == 'Responder')]
In[]:
sns.relplot(
    data=data_subset, x='TimePoint',y='Basophils', kind='line',
    )

plt.show()

It automatically computes the mean and confidence intervals (95% by default) for each timepoint.

Your turn!

Make a lineplot to compare, for the "Basophils" count, the trends over time between Responders and Non-Responders, in all treatment arms.
